'''Kate Brown''' (born June 21, 1960) is an [[United States|American]] politician and member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], She is the current [[Oregon Secretary of State]] and was elected to that office in the [[Oregon state elections, 2008|2008 elections]].<ref name=SoSwin>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/oregonian/index.ssf?/base/news/1225869920296640.xml&coll=7 |title= Democrats sweep to capture statewide jobs |work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=2008-11-05 |accessdate=2008-11-05}}</ref> Prior to becoming Secretary of State, Brown served in the [[Oregon State Senate]] representing Oregon's 21st senate district, which includes portions of Northeast and Southeast [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] and [[Milwaukie, Oregon|Milwaukie]]. During that time, Brown was elected [[Senate Majority Leader|Majority Leader]] from 2004 to 2009, and was the first woman to hold that post.  As Oregon does not have a lieutenant governor, Brown is first in line to succeed to the office of [[Governor of Oregon|governor]] if the governor should become unable to perform the duties of the office.

==Early life==
Brown was born in [[Torrej<U+00F3>n de Ardoz]], [[Spain]], but was raised mostly in [[Minnesota]]. She earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Environmental Conservation with a certificate in [[Women<U+2019>s Studies]] from the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]], and a [[juris doctor|law degree]] and Certificate in [[Environmental Law]] from the Northwestern School of Law at [[Lewis and Clark College]].

==Career==
===Law===
Brown has taught at [[Portland State University]], and practiced family and juvenile law. She currently practices as an attorney with the Juvenile Rights Project, a [[non-profit]] [[corporation]] in Portland, providing legal services to children and families with both defense and advocacy programs.

===Politics===
She began her legislative career in 1991 in the [[Oregon House of Representatives]], where she was reelected to a second term before being elected to the Senate in 1996.

In July 2007, Brown announced that she would give up her seat in the Oregon Senate to be a candidate for [[Oregon Secretary of State]] in 2008.<ref name=sos>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/oregonian/stories/index.ssf?/base/news/1184032545221820.xml&coll=7|title=Senator joins secretary of state race|last=Kost|first=Ryan |work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=2007-07-10 |accessdate=2007-07-11}}</ref> On May 20, 2008, Brown won the [[Oregon Democratic primary, 2008|election for the Democratic nomination]] for Secretary of State, and on November 5 she won the general election by a 51-46% margin against Republican candidate [[Rick Dancer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=2466 |title=
Political Notebook: Bisexual, lesbian politicians stump in SF |last=Bajko|first=Matthew S. |work=[[Bay Area Reporter]] |date=2007-11-22|accessdate=2008-05-15}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Brown lives in [[Portland, Oregon]] with her husband Dan.  She has two stepchildren Dylan and Jessie. She [[sexual identity|identifies]] as [[bisexual]] and is the highest-ranking bisexual politician in the United States.<ref>[http://www.365gay.com/news/lesbian-becomes-highest-elected-lgbt-state-official-in-country/ Lesbian becomes highest elected LGBT state official in country]</ref>

== Awards and distinctions ==
* 2004 Recipient, National Public and Community Service Award from the [[American Mental Health Counselors Association]]
* Past Chair, [[Council of State Governments]] West
*"Profiles in Courage" Award, [[Basic Rights Oregon]]
* Legislator of the Year Award, [[Oregon Psychological Association]]
* Outstanding Achievement Award, Oregon Family Support Network
* Woman of Achievement Award, Oregon Commission for Women

